total ventilation with increased efficiency","Decrease in tidal volume with increased respiratory rate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct response is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportional increase in ventilation with metabolic rate\u003C/strong\u003E. As exercise intensity increases, ventilation increases in proportion to metabolic demand and carbon dioxide production. This is achieved through increases in both tidal volume and respiratory rate, allowing precise matching of gas exchange to metabolic requirements.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecrease in tidal volume with increased respiratory rate\u003C/strong\u003E - During exercise, both tidal volume and respiratory rate increase to meet demands\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFixed increase in ventilation regardless of exercise intensity\u003C/strong\u003E - Ventilation varies based on exercise intensity and metabolic needs\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed increase in ventilation after exercise begins\u003C/strong\u003E - Ventilatory response begins immediately with exercise onset\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecrease in total ventilation with increased efficiency\u003C/strong\u003E - Total ventilation increases during exercise despite improved efficiency\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe precise matching of ventilation to metabolic demand is achieved through multiple mechanisms including central command, peripheral chemoreceptors, and mechanoreceptors in exercising muscles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During exercise, ventilation increases proportionally to metabolic demand and carbon dioxide production.","Ventilation increases primarily through increases in both tidal volume and respiratory rate.","The respiratory control centre responds to chemical and neural 